## 📝 Interview Questions

**Q1. What is the difference between `localStorage` and `sessionStorage`?**
> Both store key-value string data in the browser. `localStorage` persists indefinitely (until explicitly cleared). `sessionStorage` is cleared when the tab or browser is closed. Both are accessible only by JS (not sent to server automatically).

**Q2. Can you store an object directly in `localStorage`?**
> No. `localStorage` only stores strings. You must serialize with `JSON.stringify()` before storing and `JSON.parse()` after retrieving.

**Q3. What is the difference between `localStorage` and cookies?**
> `localStorage` stores more data (~5MB), never expires, and is not sent to the server. Cookies have a ~4KB limit, can have expiry dates, and are automatically sent with every HTTP request — making them useful for server-side authentication.

**Q4. What does `location.replace()` do differently from `location.assign()`?**
> Both navigate to a new URL. `assign()` adds a new entry to the browser history (user can click Back). `replace()` replaces the current history entry — the user cannot go back to the previous page.

**Q5. What is `URLSearchParams` and why is it useful?**
> It provides an easy way to parse, read, and modify URL query strings. Instead of manually splitting `?id=5&color=red`, you use `params.get("id")` for clean access.

**Q6. What is `requestAnimationFrame` and why is it better than `setInterval` for animations?**
> `requestAnimationFrame` syncs to the browser's repaint cycle (~60fps), pauses when the tab is hidden (saving resources), and produces smoother animations. `setInterval` fires at a fixed rate regardless of frame rate or tab visibility.

**Q7. What is `performance.now()` used for?**
> It returns a high-resolution timestamp (in milliseconds). Used for measuring how long code takes to execute — much more precise than `Date.now()` for performance profiling.

